`<T>` is a type parameter — a placeholder replaced when you create the class.

```java
class Box<T> {             // T = any type
    T value;
    Box(T val) { value = val; }
    T get() { return value; }
}

Box<String> strBox = new Box<>("hello");
Box<Integer> intBox = new Box<>(42);
```

Run this — one class, different types.

starter:
class Box<T> {
    private T value;

    Box(T value) { this.value = value; }
    T get()       { return value; }
    void set(T v) { value = v; }

    @Override
    public String toString() { return "Box[" + value + "]"; }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box<String>  strBox = new Box<>("Hello");
        Box<Integer> intBox = new Box<>(42);
        Box<Double>  dblBox = new Box<>(3.14);

        System.out.println(strBox);
        System.out.println(intBox);
        System.out.println(dblBox);

        strBox.set("Updated");
        System.out.println(strBox);
    }
}

instruction:
Methods can be generic independently of their class:

```java
static <T> void swap(T[] arr, int i, int j) {
    T temp = arr[i];
    arr[i] = arr[j];
    arr[j] = temp;
}
```

Write a generic `printArray` and `reverse` method.

starter:
import java.util.Arrays;

public class Main {
    static <T> void printArray(T[] arr) {
        for (T item : arr) System.out.print(item + " ");
        System.out.println();
    }

    static <T> T[] reverse(T[] arr) {
        T[] copy = Arrays.copyOf(arr, arr.length);
        for (int i = 0, j = copy.length-1; i < j; i++, j--) {
            T tmp = copy[i]; copy[i] = copy[j]; copy[j] = tmp;
        }
        return copy;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[]  words  = {"Java", "is", "awesome"};
        Integer[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

        printArray(words);
        printArray(numbers);
        printArray(reverse(numbers));
    }
}

instruction:
Restrict `T` to specific types using `extends`:

```java
// T must be a Number (or subclass):
static <T extends Number> double sum(List<T> list) {...}
```

This lets you call `.doubleValue()` on T because you know it's a Number.

starter:
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    // T must be a Number — lets us call .doubleValue()
    static <T extends Number> double sum(List<T> list) {
        double total = 0;
        for (T item : list) total += item.doubleValue();
        return total;
    }

    static <T extends Comparable<T>> T max(T a, T b) {
        return a.compareTo(b) >= 0 ? a : b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(sum(List.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)));
        System.out.println(sum(List.of(1.5, 2.5, 3.0)));

        System.out.println(max(10, 20));
        System.out.println(max("apple", "zebra"));
    }
}

import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    // ? — accepts List<String>, List<Integer>, etc.
    static void printList(List<?> list) {
        for (Object item : list) System.out.print(item + " ");
        System.out.println();
    }

    // ? extends Number — accepts List<Integer>, List<Double>, etc.
    static double sumNumbers(List<? extends Number> list) {
        double sum = 0;
        for (Number n : list) sum += n.doubleValue();
        return sum;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        printList(List.of("a", "b", "c"));
        printList(List.of(1, 2, 3));
        System.out.println(sumNumbers(List.of(1, 2, 3, 4)));
        System.out.println(sumNumbers(List.of(1.5, 2.5)));
    }
}
